  "text": "The JCE (Java Cryptography Extension) provider architecture in OpenJDK is built on a layered design that provides pluggable cryptographic service providers. Here is the audit of the key components:\n\n## Core Architecture Components\n\n### 1. Provider Framework (java.security.Provider)\nFile: `src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Provider.java`\n\nThe abstract `Provider` class (line 1) is the foundation of the JCE architecture. Each cryptographic provider extends this class. Key components include:\n- **Service Inner Class (line 1500)**: Represents a single cryptographic service (algorithm) offered by a provider. Contains type, algorithm name, implementation class name, and aliases.\n- **putService() method (line 1221)**: Protected method allowing providers to register services with themselves.\n- **getService() method (line 1136)**: Retrieves a specific Service by type and algorithm name.\n- **getServices() method (line 1183)**: Returns all services offered by the provider.\n\n### 2. Provider Registry (java.security.Security)\nFile: `src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Security.java`\n\nThe `Security` class manages all registered cryptographic providers globally. Key methods include:\n- **addProvider() method (line 505)**: Registers a new provider in the system, returning its position in the provider list.\n- **getProvider() method (line 559)**: Retrieves a specific provider by name.\n- **getProviders() method (line 543)**: Returns all registered providers as an array.\n- **getProviders(String filter) method (line 624)**: Filters providers by service filter criteria.\n- **getProviders(Map filter) method (line 702)**: Advanced provider filtering using a map of criteria.\n\n### 3. SunJCE Provider Implementation\nFile: `src/java.base/share/classes/com/sun/crypto/provider/SunJCE.java`\n\nThe `SunJCE` class (line 125 constructor) is a concrete implementation of the Provider abstract class. It provides cryptographic algorithms including:\n- RSA encr